    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm looking into switching my 9 year old Lab over to a higher protein diet because his vet recommended it for his muscle mass, but i'm a bit confused by the labels. what's a good protein to fat ratio i should be looking for in a senior dog food? i dont want him getting too heavy but i want him to stay strong.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Look for a protein-to-fat ratio that's solid, but don't let the numbers scare you off, as the best food is often the one that tastes good to your dog. A good starting point for a senior dog, especially one needing muscle support, is somewhere in the range of 25% to 35% protein. Higher protein is good for muscle, but if it's *too* high, you might end up with a lot of excess fat, which is what you want to avoid if you're worried about weight gain. Always check the ingredients list, not just the big flashy numbers, for the actual source of that protein.",
      "source": "target",
