    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so if i'm looking at a bag that has 30% protein and 12% fat, does that sound okay for an older lab? also how do i tell if the protein source is actually high quality vs just cheap fillers?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A 30% protein and 12% fat ratio sounds like a decent starting point for an older Lab, especially if your vet is pushing for that muscle support. It's not overly lean, which is good for an older dog who needs sustained energy, but it's not so high that it'll make him look like a furry, overstuffed sack of bones. To check the quality of the protein source, look at the first few ingredients. You want to see recognizable, high-value animal proteins listed right at the top, like chicken, salmon, or beef. If you see things like \"by-products\" or long strings of obscure powders, that's usually just cheap filler, not the good stuff.",
